  "summary": "McArthur concludes his lengthy deduction by proposing that Kumagai might be the great-grandchild of Medvedev. He suggests that Medvedev had a mistress in Japan who was pregnant at the time of his death, and that this descendant may be seeking revenge against the Inagaki family. Detective Jouji is visibly affected by this theory, though McArthur clarifies it is merely a reliable scenario for investigation.\n\nThe meeting is interrupted by Kuwabara, who enters the room and refutes the accusation. Kuwabara asserts that his background is clear and claims that Medvedev’s actual great-grandchild is female. Although McArthur attempts to suggest that Kuwabara might be motivated by Kanai's inheritance, the group loses confidence in the detective. Mutsu dismisses the meeting, leaving McArthur defeated.\n\nFollowing the meeting, the narrator reunites with Matsuzaki, who has returned from a retreat at Mount Kumashira. The narrator recounts the recent murders of Mirei and Kanae, as well as the revelation that Yuzuha is Kikyo. Mutsu reflects on the case, noting that while he felt powerless, the experience provided him with personal growth. Mutsu also warns McArthur to be careful, noting that McArthur's intelligence makes him dangerous.\n\nLater, Mutsu takes the narrator to National K University Hospital. Mutsu reveals he has an appointment with Professor Nakatani, a world-renowned pioneer in Japanese neuroscience, though he does not immediately disclose his specific motive for the visit.",
